sec.p:
The set B(v) can be seen as a set of sets if each node w∈B(v) is replaced by N(w)∩U(v). In this respect, the calculation of Fw(v) can be formulated as a set cover problem, the minimisation version of which is known to be NP-hard [30]. The greedy set cover (GSC) algorithm can be used to produce Fw(v). GSC is a well-known polynomial time algorithm [30, 31] that adopts a greedy approach in order to provide an approximation of the optimal solution. Although all DP algorithms adopt GSC, they take a different approach in calculating B(v) and U(v). This is because the performance of GSC in terms of Fw(v) minimisation and time complexity depends on the size of B(v) and U(v). The most representative algorithms are as follows:
dominant pruning (DP) [20], in which U(v)=N(N(v))−N(u);
partial dominant pruning (PDP) [21], where U(v)=N(N(v))−(N(v)∩N(u));
total dominant pruning (TDP) [21] with U(v)=N(N(v))−N(N(u)).
At the same time, B(v)=N(v)−N(u), for all schemes. TDP defines the smallest U(v) set, therefore minimises the number of elected forward nodes while having the smallest time requirements. In Section 3.1, we will provide more insight on the performance of DP schemes.
